The vulnerability is a stack buffer overflow in the following code in `shell.c`:

```c
while ((*cur != '\n') && (*cur != '\r') && (*cur != 0)) {
    if (*cur == 0)
        break;
    arg[i++] = *cur++;
}
arg[i] = 0;
```

Here, `arg` is defined as `char arg[400];`, but there is no bounds checking on `i`. If the input is longer than 399 characters, this will write past the end of the buffer, causing a stack buffer overflow.

**To fix this:**
- Add a check to ensure `i < sizeof(arg) - 1` before writing to `arg[i++]`.

I will now generate a patch to fix this.
```diff
--- a/shell.c
+++ b/shell.c
@@ -1145,10 +1145,14 @@
-        while ((*cur != '\n') && (*cur != '\r') && (*cur != 0)) {
-            if (*cur == 0)
-                break;
-            arg[i++] = *cur++;
-        }
-        arg[i] = 0;
+        while ((*cur != '\n') && (*cur != '\r') && (*cur != 0)) {
+            if (*cur == 0)
+                break;
+            if (i >= (int)(sizeof(arg) - 1))
+                break;
+            arg[i++] = *cur++;
+        }
+        arg[i] = 0;
```

